					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12818435#post-4427217</guid>
				<title>Minor Typos/Grammatical fixes</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12818435/scp-4651#post-4427217</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 19 Nov 2019 18:48:47 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>glewmie</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>3448977</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <blockquote> <p>Workers will not leave SCP-4651 <strong>voluntary</strong> and will vanish if forcible extraction is attempted, re-emerging the next day.</p> </blockquote> <p><em>Voluntary</em> is an adjective.<br /> &quot;Your voluntary participation is appreciated.&quot;</p> <p><em>Voluntarily</em> is an adverb.<br /> &quot;They participated voluntarily.&quot;</p> <blockquote> <p>Furthermore, workers <strong>have proven unable</strong> to recall details of a life beyond their employment, instead placing extreme value on their standing within the company.</p> </blockquote> <p>'have proven' vs. 'have been proven'</p> <p>&quot;The lab boys have proven that the rations are nutritionally complete.&quot;<br /> The lab boys are doing the proving. They proved a fact about the rations.</p> <p>&quot;The rations have been proven to actually not be nutritionally complete.&quot;<br /> A fact about the rations has been proven.</p> <p>Right now, your sentence reads like the workers are doing the proving, but you probably mean that the research is proving something.</p> <p>Beyond that, it was a fun, short read. Thank you for sharing.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
					<item>
				<guid>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12818435#post-4427209</guid>
				<title>I don&#039;t know why i like this...</title>
				<link>http://www.scpwiki.com/forum/t-12818435/scp-4651#post-4427209</link>
				<description></description>
				<pubDate>Tue, 19 Nov 2019 18:35:53 +0000</pubDate>
				<wikidot:authorName>Zesc</wikidot:authorName>				<wikidot:authorUserId>5703022</wikidot:authorUserId>				<content:encoded>
					<![CDATA[
						 <p>&#8230;but here, take my +1. British spelling of &quot;storey&quot;, super-human gunslinging action and an anomalous company that manages to be congruent earned you a <em>promotion</em>.</p> <p>Anyway, my only nitpick is the image of the interior. Is it really possible? Especially &quot;distorted by explosives&quot;&#8230; why would they use that picture in the first place? There's no reason for it to exist, and it seems to be low-effort.</p> 
				 	]]>
				</content:encoded>							</item>
